Development of MASLD Treatment Model Assumptions

Author

Andy Wilson
NHS Transformation Unit

Published

09 February 2025

1 Introduction

Note

This is a live document that will be continually updated during the course of this project. Literature review is currently on-going to establish assumptions and sensitivties to be applied within the model.

The purpose of this document is to identify the relevant and appropriate sources for each of the MASLD treatment model assumptions. This will include:

  • An explanation of why this assumption needs to be determined.
  • Discussion of literature that provides estimates of the assumption including the geographical area, time period of the data collection and any important limitations.
  • The suggested value of this assumption to be used in the model and the range of sensitivities to be applied.


2 Starting Population Assumptions Development

This section discusses the development of assumptions related to determining the initial starting populations of eligible patients. The flow of determining the starting population are shown in the diagram below:

2.1 Prevalence and Sub-Population Prevalence

2.1.1 Why is this required?

The prevalence of MASLD & MASH is necessary to establish the population of patients that could be considered for each of the four treatment options. By establishing the prevalence this will enable the initial population to be calculated for MASLD patients across England. Further assumptions will then be applied to determine the percentage of this population that is eligible for the treatment.

2.1.2 Findings from Literature

The table below provides an overview of the estimates of the prevalence of MASLD and MASH from relevant literature:

Reference Estimate of Prevalence (95%CI) Location Comments
(Lekakis and Paptheodoridis 2024) MASLD: 32% (30 - 35%) Global Meta-analysis of NAFLD worldwide
(Younossi et al. 2016) MASLD: 25.2% (22.1 - 28.7%) Global Meta-analysis of NAFLD
(Younossi 2019) MASLD: 25% Global Review of global risk factors
(Younossi 2019) MASLD: 24% Europe Review of global risk factors
(Younossi et al. 2023) MASLD: 25.1% (20.6 - 30.3%) Western Europe Systematic Review
(Younossi et al. 2023) MASLD: 38.0% (33.7 - 42.5%) Global Systematic Review - 2016 to 2019
(Alenezi et al. 2022) MASLD: 23.7% (20.6 - 26.8%) UK Systematic Review and meta-analysis
(Younossi et al. 2023) MASH: 5.27% Global Systematic Review
(Younossi et al. 2023) MASH: 4.02% Western Europe Systematic Review
(Younossi et al. 2023) MASH: 4.02% Western Europe Systematic Review

2.3 Co-morbidities and Risk Factors

2.3.1 Why is this required?

It is important to consider the expected overlap of patients with MASLD and other conditions such as Obesity or Diabetes. Patients who have MASLD but are being treated on an obesity pathway with a GLP-1 agonist may not be prescribed one of the four treatments in addition to their obesity treatment. Therefore, an estimate of patients with MASLD to exclude from the treatment population is required.

2.3.2 Findings from Literature

2.3.2.1 Obesity

The table below shows the estimated prevalence of obesity for patients diagnosed with MASLD or MASH:

Reference Group Estimated Prevalence (95% CI) Location Comments
(Basu, Noureddin, and Clark 2022) MASLD 51% USA MASLD patients with obesity
(Pustjens et al. 2024) MASLD - All ages 89.5% USA MASLD patients with obesity (US Abdo confirmed)
(Pustjens et al. 2024) MASLD - 20-40 83.1% USA MASLD patients with obesity (US Abdo confirmed)
(Pustjens et al. 2024) MASLD - 40-60 92.4% USA MASLD patients with obesity (US Abdo confirmed)
(Pustjens et al. 2024) MASLD - 60-80 92.9% USA MASLD patients with obesity (US Abdo confirmed)
(Basu, Noureddin, and Clark 2022) MASH 82% USA MASH patients with obesity
